CANT STOP PT.1 |Today I celebrate, God, Gratitude, and self-worth.  Though I know I’m divinely loved and protected, I have not always valued, loved, and protected myself and my energy.  I’m thankful that the hard lessons of yesterday have guided me to the self worth and self love I have for myself today.  I am a very unique being of grace and love and I do not take that back for anything.  There will NEVER be another Tony Tzar and I am so proud of who I’ve become and what I’ve grown through.  Thankful for God showing me this and also now allowing me to experience this from my new surroundings.  I encourage all, but especially my fellow black men….. please PLEASE PLEASE free yourself from all conditioning,  live your truth unapologetically, and PROTECT YOURSELF AND YOUR ENERGY.  We ALL as people, every creed every melanin level contain some kind of incredible magic.  Search for that within and choose Love as your main tool to navigate through this mystery of life.  Love. Trust me, if you knew my story……… I don’t look like what I’ve been through. | 🎼 Can’t Stop- Maro & Blanda| #Love #SelfLove #NewDay #Dance #NeverGiveUp

Club/Street Footwork & Afro Origins.- I’ve learned through the many years of studying dance(especially street and cultural) that many of our footwork origins in club & street dance have many direct and indirect correlations to African club and street dance via Afro-centric cultural influences. Even though we’re dancing to Gqom music(originated in Durban) this routine seen is actually most Bmore club steps a dance with heavy footwork that originated in the streets & clubs of Baltimore Maryland. 

This class was my Beg/Int. In which we mainly covered drills from Azonto(Ghana), Amapiano, Pantsula, Kwaito(South Africa), Kuduro(Angola), and Ndombolo(Congo) , Passinho(Brazil), and even Traditional African Dances of Togo(my first discipline of dance). Then connecting these styles to Afro-American street dances such as Bmore footwork, Chicago footwork, Detroit Jit, Memphis Jook, Jersey Club, & ect.  It’s actually very interesting how many steps and grooves all of these dances have that are alike. 

I would encourage all that love street/hip hop/club dance to actually research and study African dance.  Not just the new popular moves but also origins and traditional.  Many people to this dance ask how/why I move the way that I move and I always reply because I started with Traditional Cultural Dance.  African, Polynesian, & Filipino dance first.  Then came everything else. 

Thank you so much @urbananimal_official for being so receptive of my teachings and amazing with your energy and love. 🫶🏾

Just thought I’d share a few more seconds of my process and a few thoughts pertaining to PROCESS all in a post.  My most favorite part of creating is my PROCESS and most people involved in my creations also voice the same opinion. There’s always something special about PROCESS in general to me.  A lot of times we mix up PROGRESS and process.  I’ve found that process without the expectation of progress allows progress to happen a lot more organically.  Many times we don’t add patience to the equation of process which in turn adds a lot of unnecessary stress.  PATIENCE is a virtue of TRUST so trusting your PROCESS means you are willing to exercise, grow, and practice PATIENCE.  Are you TRUSTING YOUR PROCESS?  Most likely if you’re stressing, you’re not.  Enjoy your process, Learn from each process with no expectation except that the outcome will be the best possible outcome.  Have PATIENCE and TRUST YOUR PROCESS! 

P.S.- This is more a message for life in General not solely for creation. 😉🫶🏾

This a lil late but only because I’ve been a little busy 🎄🎅🏾. It’s an honor to officially post that I’m touring with the one and only @mariahcarey .  It’s been nothing but pure joy and amazing times and company.  I’m beyond grateful to be spending my holiday with this group of incredible souls.  @fatima_noir there is no other like you,  I’ve learned so much just by observing you gracefully master your craft and exercise your genius.  @iamtiarivera and @iamdjdubz you two not only did a top-notch job on choreography but the safe and honorable space you guys curated set us up with one of the best work environments I ever experienced.  @therealdebbieallen The honor of working with you and also being able to talk with you is unforgettable and will be with me til my dying day.  Life is life’n right now and I’m loving it!🫶🏾🔮🎄

Went to Kansas City and spent 2 nights in a museum.  Meditated on and learned a few things

“Know this.  Your vision will always be obscured from the outside perspective.  Same with your character.  As long as you give others power you will see your self through their eyes and what a tragedy is this.  Only two entities can see you clearly Self & God.  Others will just have to wait til fruition and by that time you’ll be onto the next chapter of self.  Be okay with that and grateful for the blessing of a continuous new day and opportunity to co-created. Love to all”
-Tzar
